(13, 'cgreen', 'crisgreen329@gmail.com', 'cgr33n', 'wTOIREw0ZXZ74KBGxSFuH0FPysOXTe', 'Favorites~Trinity~Secret~Questions~~Cross ref', null, 9, '0:1:1:1:1:1:0', 'Cris G', '2023-02-12 19:53:14', '107.213.151.96', null, '0:1:56:2:13:0~5:1:56:2:13:0~0:1:56:2:13:0~5:1:56:2:13:0~0:1:56:2:13:0~5:0:9:8:12:0~5:0:24:1:17:0~5:0:25:3:40:0~5:0:25:1:20:0~44:0:0:1:0:0~5:0:26:48:10:0~5:0:25:1:20:0~5:0:25:3:38:0~0:0:25:3:64:0~5:0:25:3:64:0~5:1:49:1:14:0~0:1:49:4:6:0~5:1:49:4:6:0~0:1:49:4:5:0~5:1:49:4:5:0~0:1:49:4:4:0~5:1:49:4:4:0~0:1:49:4:1:0~0:0:26:42:16:0~5:0:26:42:16:0~0:0:26:42:16:0', '0,1,61,1,nav2;5,0,23,42,6;0,0,5,17,nav18;0,1,40,3,nav9;0,1,41,3,nav17;0,1,60,5,nav10;0,1,41,14,nav36;0,1,41,7,nav11;0,1,43,21,nav17;0,1,44,11,nav28;0,1,42,1,nav13;0,1,66,19,nav17;0,1,40,19,nav12;0,1,40,26,nav6;0,1,41,7,nav19;0,1,44,7,nav14;0,1,41,8,nav10;0,1,41,10,nav51;0,1,41,7,nav34;0,1,41,5,nav41;0,1,46,5,nav8;0,1,48,4,nav21;0,0,1,1,nav1;0,1,40,23,nav34;5,1,43,14,2;0,1,44,21,nav7;5,1,44,8,27;5,1,43,7,52;5,1,40,26,6;5,1,45,5,7;5,1,40,27,46;5,1,42,18,25;5,1,40,7,6;5,1,40,6,12;5,1,44,1,19;0,1,40,1,nav1', null, '<p>Ask JJW about brackets in comms like Exod. 12:14</p> <p>Equal signs:</p> <p>Need to look at Exo 12:40; Matt 9:38; 14:34; 16:18; 18:28; Mark 7:3, 30; 12:42.</p> <p>Luke 9:42; 19:37; John 1:18; 4:24; 9:3; Acts 7:55; 16:11; Rom 8:7; 10:9; 1 Cor 14:7; Gal 1:12; 6:6; Eph 1:19; 1 Thes 1:1; 2:5</p> <p>Tit 1:8; Heb 5:12; 1John 3:16; 5:20</p> <p>There&#39;s also one in the &quot;Introduction to the REV,&quot; nd one in Appx 5, 6, and 9</p> <p>&ldquo;Peace if possible; truth at all costs,&rdquo; Martin Luther.</p> <p>REV commentary on Galatians REV Commentary on the book of Galatians REV introduction to Galatians REV introduction to the book of Galatians book commentary on Galatians book commentary on the book of Galatians (kinda stupid) book introduction to Galatians (not great) book introduction to the book of Galatians (kinda stupid)</p> <p>The next time you go to the woodsware tort site (if you do..) you&#39;ll be asked to sign in:</p> <p>Username: satuser<br /> Passwd: sat312user</p> <p>To undo a link: wrap the section with [noparse] book, ch:vs [/noparse]</p> <p>In your myrev notes, you can type &quot;my note on book ch:vs&quot; and it will turn to a link and take you there.</p> <p>Rob&rsquo;s instructions: I think I have it so that if you type &quot;commentary on book ch:vs&quot;, that will link, too. Also Appx&#39;s, and Greek words. For appx&#39;s, you need &quot;see appendix X&quot;.<br /> For Greek words, you need the pound sign followed by the Strong&#39;s number. #1234 should link to the Greek word 1234 (whatever it is), and #01234 would link to the Hebrew word. Hebrew Strongs numbers are always prefaced with 0 (zero). Maybe someday I&#39;ll make it work with G1234 and H1234. But that&#39;s not in place now.</p> <p>ADMINISTRATIONS Eph. 3:2</p> <p>ANGELS Heb. 13:2</p> <p>ANOINTED/MESSIAH/CHRIST Ps. 45:7</p> <p>ARAMAIC Some passages, such as Jeremiah 10:11, Daniel 2:4&ndash;7, Daniel 2:28, Ezra 4:8&ndash;6:8, Ezra 7:12&ndash;26, and possibly the whole book of Job, were originally written in Aramaic, another ancient language.</p> <p>BAPTISM Matt. 28:19; Luke 3:16; John 20:22; Acts 19:5</p> <p>BIRTH OF CHRIST The birth of Christ in chronological order, it is: Luke 1:5-80; Matt. 1:18-25; Luke 2:1-30; Matt. 2:1-22. Then Matt. 2:23 and Luke 2:39-40 summary about Jesus growing up in Nazareth.</p> <p>Then Matt. 2:23 and Luke 2:39-40 are both summary statements about Jesus growing up in Nazareth.</p> <p>BOOK OF LIFE &ldquo;the book.&rdquo;This is a reference to &ldquo;the Book of Life,&rdquo; the book that has the names of all those who will be granted everlasting life (cp. Exod. 32:32; Ps. 69:28(some versions have it as 69:29); Phil 4:3; Rev. 3:5; 13:8; 17:8; 20:12, 15; 21:27).</p> <p>Commentary for Isaiah 42:6 Besides those promises, the Old Testament had a number of verses that spoke of Gentiles being included in the Messianic Kingdom, which meant they were granted everlasting life (Ps. 102:15; Isa. 2:2-4; 19:23-25; 42:6; 49:6; 51:4-5; 56:3-7; 60:3; 66:18-21; Ezek. 39:21, 27; Micah 4:2; Hag. 2:7; Zech. 8:22).</p> <p>BURNT OFFERINGS Exodus 29:13; Amos 5:22</p> <p>CHRONOLGY Matt. 25:32 chronology of END TIMES EVENTS. Also Rev. 21:1</p> <p>CHRONOLOGY BIRTH OF CHRIST The birth of Christ in chronological order, it is: Luke 1:5-80; Matt. 1:18-25; Luke 2:1-30; Matt. 2:1-22. Then Matt. 2:23 and Luke 2:39-40 summary about Jesus growing up in Nazareth.</p> <p>CHRONOLOGY from the CRUCIFIXION TO DAY OF PENTECOST Luke 23:50; John 18:13</p> <p>CHRONOLOGY of the last week of Jesus&rsquo; life &ndash; John 18:13</p> <p>CHRONOLOGY of the death and resurrection of Jesus &ndash; Matt. 12:40</p> <p>CHRONOLOGY Mark 14:25: Between 3 and 6 AM. In NT times, the day was divided into 12 hours (John 11:9) and the night into 4 watches: 1st: 6-9 PM; 2nd: 9 PM -midnight; 3rd: midnight -3 AM; 4th: 3-6 AM (Mark 13:35). ALSO SEE Matt: 20:3: At the time of Christ the day was divided into 12 hours starting at roughly 6 AM. Thus the third hour was about 9 AM, the sixth hour was noon, the ninth hour was 3 PM, and the eleventh hour was about 5 PM.</p> <p>CROWNS 1 Cor. 9:25; 1 Thess. 2:19</p> <p>DEATH Eccl. 3:19; 6:6; Ps. 49:20 &amp; commentary; Acts 20:24 psuche, Paul; Ezekiel 37:12; Isaiah 26:14; 38:1; 38:11; 38:17; 38:18; Job 3:17; Gen. 25:8; Ps. 115:17; 1 Cor. 15:20, 26; 2 Thess. 1:9; Heb. 13:14; Also see commentary on Mark 1:24 and John 5:26. Queen of the South Matt. 12:42. John 3:13. 1 Cor. 15:18. Gen. 37:35. Also see Deut. 32:39. And John 10:17. Job 20:7. <span style="background-color:#ffff66;">JOHN 3:16</span>; <span style="background-color:#ffff99;">ROM. 6:23</span>.</p> <p>1 Thessalonians 4:15 also has some wording that we must pay careful attention to. It says that &ldquo;we who are alive&hellip;will certainly not precede those who have fallen asleep.&rdquo; Why would Paul say that? If when a believer dies they are in heaven with the Lord as Christian tradition says, then dead Christians have already preceded living Christians to heaven! If what orthodox Christianity teaches about the dead being alive with Christ is correct, then Paul should have written something such as, &ldquo;those who are dead have preceded us and are now in the presence of the Lord.&rdquo; Instead, he consoles the Thessalonians by saying that living Christians will not go into the presence of Christ before dead Christians. But he does not say that because dead Christians go to heaven when they die; he says it because dead Christians will be raised up to be with Christ before living Christians are changed and go up to be with Christ (1 Thess. 4:16 and 17).</p> <p>2 Tim. 1:10</p> <p>1 Tim. 6:16 only God is immortal</p> <p>Ps. 146:4 thoughts perish; Ps. 94:17 silence; Prov. 13:9 the lamp of the wicked will go out;</p> <p class="normal" style="margin-top:16px; margin-bottom:16px"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span sans-serif="" style="font-family:Arial,">&ldquo;For that which befalleth the sons of men befalleth beasts; even one thing befalleth them: as the one dieth, so dieth the other; yea, they have all one breath; so that a man hath no preeminence above a beast: for all is vanity. All go unto one place; all are of the dust, and all turn to dust again. (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Ecc. 3:19-20</span></a> KJV).</span></span></span></p> <p class="normal" style="margin-top:16px; margin-bottom:16px"><span style="font-size:11pt"><span style="line-height:normal"><span sans-serif="" style="font-family:Arial,">Appendix 4:</span> <span sans-serif="" style="font-family:Arial,">There are many verses that show that when the body died, the person, both body and soul, were totally dead. Death and being in <em>sheol</em> is compared to sleep in many verses (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Job 7:21</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">14:12-14</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Psalm 13:3</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">90:5</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Dan. 12:2</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">John 11:11</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">1 Cor. 11:30</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">15:51</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">1 Thess. 4:14</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">5:10</span></a>). The comparison is valid because just as there is no consciousness in sleep, there is none in death. Once a person dies, he does not remember God (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Ps. 6:5</span></a>). In fact, dead people &ldquo;know nothing&rdquo; (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Ecc. 9:5</span></a>). They cannot praise God or speak of His goodness (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Ps. 30:9</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">115:17</span></a>; <a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Isa. 38:18</span></a>), they cannot thank God or hope in Him (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Isa. 38:18</span></a>); and they have no knowledge or wisdom (<a href="https://www.revisedenglishversion.com/appx/SIT"><span style="color:#1155cc">Ecc. 9:10</span></a>). Obviously, these dead people are not rejoicing in heaven or suffering in &ldquo;Hell.&rdquo;</span></span></span></p> <p>DIVINE COUNCIL Gen. 1:26; Job 1:6. Also look up &ldquo;watchers&rdquo; in Daniel.</p> <p>DIVORCE Exod. 21:11</p> <p>END TIMES Chronolgy of, Matt. 25:32; Rev. 21:1</p> <p>ELIJAH II Kings 2:1 Now it came to pass when Yahweh was about to take up Elijah by a whirlwind into the heavens that Elijah went with Elisha from Gilgal.</p> <p>&ldquo;into the heavens.&rdquo; Elijah was not taken &ldquo;into heaven&rdquo; where God lives, but &ldquo;into the heavens,,&rdquo; that is, into the air. He was moved from one place to another on the earth, and taken from the oversight of the other prophets, making way for the ministry of Elisha. If Elijah could &ldquo;go to heaven&rdquo; before Christ died and paid for his sin, then any person could go to heaven without the death of Christ, and Jesus Christ would not have needed to come and die for the sins of humankind (see commentary on 2 Kings 2:11).</p> <p>EVIL PEOPLE Prov. 1:18</p> <p>EXODUS, Israel time in slavery, Exodus 12:40</p> <p>FAITH 2 Cor. 4:18</p> <p>FEASTS and SABBATHS Lev. 23:2, Num. 28:11</p> <p>FIGURES OF SPEECH Irony &ndash; 1 Cor. 11:19; 2 Cor. 12:16</p> <p>FREE WILL See my note on Deut 30:19. John 6:37 (POTTER &amp; CLAY Jeremiah 18:6)</p> <p>GEHENNA Matt. 5:22</p> <p>GENTILES BLESSED Isaiah 49:8 and Isa. 42:6. Paul also contrasted &ldquo;the People&rdquo; with the Gentiles (Acts 26:23). The Gentiles were blessed in Christ (Ps. 102:15; Isa. 2:2-4; 19:23-25; 42:6; 49:6; 51:4-5; 56:3-7; 60:3; 66:18-21; Ezek. 39:21, 27; Micah 4:2; Hag. 2:7; Zech. 8:22)</p> <p>GOD IN VISIBLE FORM Isaiah 6:1 and Acts 7:55</p> <p>god/gods Ps. 58:1</p> <p>HEBREW Biblical Hebrew Grammar for Beginners Perfective and Imperfective</p> <p>The way Biblical Hebrew handles time perspectives has been one of the most widely examined and debated topics in Biblical Hebrew scholarship. While Mishnaic Hebrew and later phases of the language exhibit a fairly simple tense-based system with past, present, and future tense expressed by the verb, the system in Biblical Hebrew is more complex, as any verb form can be used in reference to any of the tenses. As a greatly simplified frame of reference, we will provide the following observations:</p> <p>&bull;Hebrew has two major conjugations, one characterized by a set of prefixes, the other by a set of suffixes. We will refer to these as the prefix conjugation and the suffix conjugation, respectively. The features of the two conjugations are discussed in the section on the Hebrew verb system.</p> <p>&bull;The conjugations represent a perspective on a situation or action. By and large, the prefix conjugation represents an action that is viewed as incomplete (ongoing, yet to occur, repetitive, habitual, etc.), and the suffix conjugation an action that is viewed as complete, that is, single and whole. These perspectives, referred to as imperfective and perfective, respectively, constitute what is known as the &ldquo;aspect system&rdquo; of Biblical Hebrew. They reflect the position taken by the discourse on the onset, duration, and completion of a situation or action.</p> <p>&bull;Forms in both conjugations occur both independently and with a prefixed vav. The vav, referred to here as &ldquo;vav consecutive,&rdquo; ties together verbs within the discourse and points to the way they relate to one another both in terms of their role in particular narratives and in terms of the aspectual perspective on the events and situations featured in the narrative. Thus, the aspectual perspective is closely tied to the technique used in piecing together the components of a Biblical narrative.</p> <p>The Narrative Sequence</p> <p>The typical narrative in Biblical Hebrew consists of a sequence of sentences whose verbs are in the imperfective (prefix conjugation). The sentences, opening with a verb in accordance with the normative sentence structure of the language (verb-subject-object), are linked with the conjunction vav in its function as a vav-consectuive, that is, a vav that indicates that the sentences are related to one another as part of a sequence within a narrative. The narrator often breaks away from this sequence in order to highlight variance within the narrative, e.g., embedded parenthetical statements or side narratives, statements that stand in contrast to others, reflections on past events, and the like. Narratives told from the &quot;complete&quot; aspectual perspective usually open with a sentence whose verb is in the perfective (suffix conjugation), and continue with a series of verbs in the imperfective with vav-consecutive. The multitude of verbs in Genesis 1 is a good example&mdash;the narrative begins with the verb ָבָראhe created (perfective) of verse 1, and continues with a series of verbs in the imperfective. In three verses (6-8), for example, we find seven instances of a verb in the imperfective with vav-consecutive:</p> <p>וַוֹיאֶמראֱאהִלֹיםיְיהִלֹיָרהִיַייְבֹוַלָֹהִיםהִויהִלֹיַמיְבהִדילֵּביןַמהִיםָלָמהִים. זַוַיַישׂאֱאהִלֹיםֶא-ָלָֹרהִיַיַוַייְבֵּדלֵּביןַלַֹהִיםֲאֶשרהִמַתַחָלָרהִיַיוֵּביןַלַֹהִיםֲאֶשרֵּמַילָלָרהִיַי;ַויְיהִלֹי-ֵּכן.חַוהִייְָראאֱאהִלֹיםָלָרהִיַיָשָמהִים;ַויְיהִלֹי-ֶיֶרבַויְיהִלֹי-ֹבֶריֹוםֵּשהִני.</p> <p>God said: Let there be a vault in the midst of the water, and let it separate between water and water. God made the vault, and separated between the water which were below the vault and the water that were above the vault, and it was so. God called the vault &ldquo;heavens&rdquo;. There was evening, and there was morning, a second day.</p> <p>In prophetic texts, where the events described are yet to take place (an &ldquo;incomplete&rdquo; perspective), a common sequence begins with a verb in the imperfective, and continues with a series of verbs in the perfective with vav-consecutive. Consider, for example, Ezekiel 14:13, a verse which opens a long statement by God on the fate of a sinful people:</p> <p>ֶבן-אָָדםֶאֶרץהִכיֶאֱחָטא- הִליהִליְמָיל- ַמַיליְוָנהִטיהִיָיהִדיָיֶליָלֹיְוָשַביְרהִתיָלהַמֵּטלֹ- ָלֶחם;יְוהִלֹיְשַליְחהִתי-ָבהָרָיביְוהִלֹיְכַרהִתיהִמֶָנלֹאָָדםויְבֵּלָֹמלֹ.</p> <p>Son of man, if a land sins against me with an act of betrayal, I stretch out my hand against it and break its supply of bread. I send famine upon it, and cut off from it both man and beast.</p> <p>The opening verb, חָטאאֱֶshe sins, is in the imperfective, and all the rest are in the perfective with vav-consecutive.</p> <p>The Narrative Sequence: Some Variations</p> <p>A reader who is aware of the conventions of the narrative sequence is likely to notice the variations that the narrator chooses to introduce and, thus, become attuned to the nuances within the narrative. Genesis 1:10, for example, includes three distinct clauses:</p> <p>ַוהִייְָראאֱאהִלֹיםַלַיָבָשלֶֹאֶרץויְלהִמיְֵּולַֹלַֹהִיםָָראַיהִיםַוַייְראאֱאהִלֹיםהִכי-טֹוב</p> <p>God called the dry land Earth</p> <p>And the gathering of waters he called Seas And God saw that it was good</p> <p>The second clause begins with an object that is fronted, that is, moved to the head of the clause, for emphasis, followed by the verb in the perfective, ָראָ, as opposed to the ַוהִייְָרא(imperfective with vav-consecutive) in the first clause. As the waters are distinguished from the dry land, the distinction, by way of a statement that stands in opposition to the previous one, is signaled by the broken narrative sequence, to which the narrator returns in the third clause of the verse. A parallel structure can be observed in Genesis 1:5, where the darkness is distinguished from the light:</p> <p>ַוהִייְָראאֱאהִלֹיםָלאֹוריֹוםיְוַלֹחֶשָָראָליְיָללֹ;ַויְיהִלֹי-ֶיֶרבַויְיהִלֹי-ֹבֶריֹוםֶאָחד. God called the light Day, and the darkness he called Night. And there was evening and there was</p> <p>morning, one day.</p> <p>The creation narrative begins with the verb ָבָראhe created (perfective) of Genesis 1:1, and continues through a series of verbs in the imperfective all the way to Genesis 2:25, with variations like the ones</p> <p>noted above introduced at a number of points. Genesis 3:1 introduces a new narrative, that of the expulsion from the Garden of Eden. Appropriately, it begins with a sentence whose structure is different, with an emphasis on the subject, the serpent, which is fronted, and the verbs in the perfective:</p> <p>יְוַלָֹנָחשָלָֹילָֹירוםהִמֹכלַחַיַלָֹשֶדלֲֹאֶשרָיָשׂלֹיְילָֹולֹאֱאהִלֹים; Now, the serpent was more cunning than any other wild creature that the Lord God had made.</p> <p>The continued narrative follows the conventions, with the verb in the imperfective with vav- consecutive:</p> <p>ַוֹיאֶמרֶאל- ָלֹהִאָשלֹאַףהִכי-אַָמראֱאהִלֹיםאֹאיְכלוהִמֹכלֵּיץַלָֹגן. ַוֹתאֶמרָלֹהִאָשלֶֹאל-ַלָֹנָחשהִמיְפהִריֵּיץ-ַלָֹגןֹנאֵּכל.</p> <p>He said to the woman: Even though God had said &ldquo;you should not eat from any tree of the garden&rdquo;... Then the woman said to the serpent: &ldquo;Of the fruit of the garden trees we should eat.&rdquo;</p> <p>The intricacies of the aspect system are not simple to describe or comprehend, but at this point it will suffice to develop awareness to the interplay of perfective and imperfective, and to the role the two conjugations play in organizing the narrative sequence.</p> <p>&copy; Esther Raizen, The University of Texas at Austin, 2007-2009</p> <p>HOLY SPIRIT Acts 15:28 See my note on Matt. 28:19. Num. 11:17</p> <p>THE REAL HOLY SPIRIT: &ldquo;THE POWER OF GOD&rdquo;</p> <p>&ldquo;The Holy Spirit shall come upon thee; and the power of the Highest shall overshadow thee&rdquo; - Lu 1:35</p> <p>NOTE: This is an excerpt from a larger article on the Holy Spirit which I posted some time ago. It may be read in its entirety at https://www.facebook.com/groups/trinities/posts/2902556250064322/</p> <p>- Parallelism</p> <p>Parallelism is a literary device, used frequently in the Bible, in which an idea is presented in two or more different ways in order to emphasize its meaning.</p> <p>The verse cited above is an example of parallelism. It parallels the phrases &ldquo;the Holy Spirit&rdquo; and &ldquo;the power of the Highest&rdquo;, showing them to be one and the same thing.</p> <p>Regarding the Bible&rsquo;s use of parallelism in talking about the Holy Spirit, the trinitarian New Catholic Encyclopedia (1967, Vol.13, P.575) tells us:</p> <p>---- &ldquo;The majority of New Testament texts reveal God&#39;s spirit as SOMETHING, not SOMEONE . . . this is especially seen in the parallelism between the Spirit and the power of God.&rdquo;</p> <p>- &ldquo;The Spirit Of God&rdquo; Means &ldquo;The Power Of God&rdquo;</p> <p>In Mt 12:28, Jesus speaks of casting out devils by the Spirit of God. Many commentaries agree that he is speaking of the power of God:</p> <p>---- &ldquo;The Spirit of God here, means the &lsquo;POWER&rsquo; of God&rdquo; - Barne&rsquo;s Notes on the NT</p> <p>---- &ldquo;A figurative way of representing the POWER of God&rdquo; - J.F.&amp;B. Comm.</p> <p>---- &ldquo;Casting out devils by a divine POWER&rdquo; - Poole&rsquo;s Comm.</p> <p>- A Force From God</p> <p>In the Bible, &ldquo;the spirit of God&rdquo; (Ge 1:2) is just what it appears to be - that power, force, or energy which comes from God. Trinitarianism would have us believe otherwise - that God&rsquo;s Spirit, as one of three persons of a triune God, is God himself. But such phrases as &ldquo;I will pour out my Spirit&rdquo; (Joe 2:28, Ac 2:17 etc), &ldquo;Thou sendest forth thy Spirit&rdquo; (Ps 104:30) and &ldquo;The Spirit of The LORD shall rest upon him&hellip;&rdquo; (Isa 11:2), make clear that God&rsquo;s spirit is not God, but power coming from, belonging to, and controlled by God - sent into the universe to effect His will.</p> <p>Part of what the Bible reveals the Holy Spirit to be is a force from God which animates and empowers those unto whom He sends it, giving them the ability to know and to do things which are beyond the normal capacity of man.</p> <p>- Bad News For Trinitarianism</p> <p>If God&rsquo;s Spirit is not a person, but rather His invisible active force manifested in the material universe, then the Doctrine of the Trinity ceases to exist. So there is little wonder that Trinitarianism has devoted endless effort to arguing against such an idea, from the fifth century even down to the present. Such arguments, however, do not change the fact that:</p> <p>---- In the Bible the Holy Spirit is not presented as a person of God, but as a manifestation of His force and power ----</p> <p>&mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; END OF ARTICLE &mdash;&mdash;&mdash;&mdash; Posted in FB by somebody</p> <p>IDIOM OF PERMISSION Isaiah 6:9; Matt. 13:13; Rom. 9:18; Exod. 4:21</p> <p>ILLEISM Hosea 1:7 Cf. Salinger: https://letthetruthcomeoutblog.wordpress.com/2022/10/25/illeism-a-response-to-a-stock-trinitarian-apologetic-move/?fbclid=IwAR2wXEFfg5TA8X_g_JT55tD8d5UsUrAiglEBFLr45JTTo9FF7U4J8fLU7Jk</p> <p>JESUS&rsquo; MINISTRY (How long was it?) John 6:4</p> <p>JOHN 1:1 Prov. 11:22; See Appendix 10</p> <p>KINGDOM OF GOD NEAR Matt. 10:23. Not the Transfiguration &ndash; Matt. 16:28</p> <p>LORD&rsquo;S SUPPER Matt. 26:17ff; Mark 14:22ff; Luke 22:17ff; John 13:1ff</p> <p>MESSIAH/CHRIST/ANOINTED Psalm 45:7</p> <p>MILLENNIAL KINGDOM Amos 9:11; Jeremiah 32:37; Isaiah 2:2 Besides those promises, the Old Testament had a number of verses that spoke of Gentiles being included in the Messianic Kingdom, which meant they were granted everlasting life (Ps. 102:15; Isa. 2:2-4; 19:23-25; 42:6; 49:6; 51:4-5; 56:3-7; 60:3; 66:18-21; Ezek. 39:21, 27; Micah 4:2; Hag. 2:7; Zech. 8:22). Commentary for: Isaiah 42:6</p> <p>NAMES OF GOD Isaiah 10:17;</p> <p>NEPHILIM <span style="font-size: 16.8px;">Gen. 6:2; 6:4</span></p> <p>NEW COVENANT 1 Cor. 11:25; Luke 22:20</p> <p>OFFERINGS Exodus 29:13; Amos 5:22</p> <p>OPEN VIEW God can change his mind &ndash; Gen. 32:14; Jer. 18:8, 1 Sam. 15:11; 2 Kings 20:5</p> <p>Search &quot;change your mind&quot;</p> <p>PAUL&rsquo;S MISSIONARY JOURNEYS (SYNOPSIS) Acts 11:30; 20:5</p> <p>PRAISE Psalms 8, 19, 23, 33, 47, 67, 84, 93, 96, 100, 111, 113, 117, 150</p> <p>PREEXISTENCE Heb. 9:28 so Christ also, having been offered one time to take away the sins of many, will appear a second time, not to atone for sin, but to save those who eagerly wait for him. Case against pre-existence? A &ldquo;second&rdquo; time, i.e. not a third, fourth, fifth,...time which means Jesus did not show up in person in the O.T.</p> <p>Matt. 1:18</p> <p>PROPHETIC PERFECT Eph. 2:6; John 13:31</p> <p>RAPTURE Saved from the wrath Rom. 5:9; 1 Thess. 1:10; 1 Thess. 5:9</p> <p>RECEIVE Dechomai &amp; Lambano Acts 8:15, 16</p> <p>RESURRECTION See CHRONOLGY</p> <p>RESURRECTION FROM THE DEAD Ps. 71:20</p> <p>REWARDS Job 34:11, Ps. 62:12; Prov. 24:12; Jer. 17:10; 32:19; Ezek. 33:20; 44:10-16; Matt. 5:11-12, 19; 6:1; 10:41-42; 16:27; 18:1-4; 25:14-29; Rom. 2:6; 1 Cor. 3:10-15; 9:24-27; 2 Cor. 5:10; Col. 3:23-25; 1 Thess. 4:6; Heb. 11:24-26; 2 John 1:8</p> <p>REVELATION See commentary on Galatians 1:11</p> <p>ROOT/SHOOT Isa. 1:11; 11:10; 14:30; Rom. 15:12; Rev. 5:5; 15:12; 22:16</p> <p>SACRED SECRET Eph. 3:9</p> <p>SENT John 6:57</p> <p>SHEEP/SHEPHERD</p> <p>Sheep imagery</p> <p>Old Testament</p> <p>Psa 44:11; Psa 44:22; Psa 49:14; Psa 74:1; Psa 78:52; Psa 79:13; Psa 95:7; Psa 100:3; Psa 119:176; Psa 144:13; Isa 13:14; Isa 53:6; Isa 53:7; Jer 12:3; Jer 23:1; Jer 50:6; Jer 50:17; Eze 34:2; Eze 34:3; Eze 34:5; Eze 34:6; Eze 34:8; Eze 34:10; Eze 34:11; Eze 34:12; Eze 34:15; Eze 34:17; Eze 34:19; Eze 34:20; Eze 34:22; Eze 34:31; Eze 45:15; Hos 12:12; Mic 2:12; Mic 5:8; Zec 10:2; Zec 11:7; Zec 13:7.</p> <p>New Testament</p> <p>Mat 7:15; Mat 9:36; Mat 10:6; Mat 10:16; Mat 12:11; Mat 12:12; Mat 15:24; Mat 18:12; Mat 25:32; Mat 25:33; Mat 26:31; Mar 6:34; Mar 14:27; Luk 15:4; Luk 15:6; Luk 17:7; Joh 2:14; Joh 2:15; Joh 5:2; Joh 10:2; Joh 10:3; Joh 10:4; Joh 10:7; Joh 10:8; Joh 10:11; Joh 10:12; Joh 10:13; Joh 10:15; Joh 10:16; Joh 10:26; Joh 10:27; Joh 21:16; Joh 21:17; Act 8:32; Rom 8:36; Heb 11:37; Heb 13:20; 1Pe 2:25; Rev 18:13.</p> <p>Shepherd Imagery</p> <p>Old Testament</p> <p>Psa 23:1; Psa 28:9; Psa 49:14; Psa 78:71; Psa 80:1; Ecc 12:11; Isa 38:12; Isa 40:11; Isa 44:28; Jer 17:16; Jer 22:22; Jer 31:10; Jer 43:12; Jer 49:19; Jer 50:44; Jer 51:23; Eze 34:5; Eze 34:8; Eze 34:12; Eze 34:15; Eze 34:23; Eze 37:24; Amos 3:12; Mic 5:4; Mic 5:6; Mic 7:14; Zec 10:2; Zec 11:4; Zec 11:7; Zec 11:9; Zec 11:15; Zec 11:16; Zec 11:17; Zec 13:7.</p> <p>New Testament</p> <p>Mat 2:6; Mat 9:36; Mat 25:32; Mat 26:31; Mar 6:34; Mar 14:27; Joh 10:2; Joh 10:11; Joh 10:12; Joh 10:14; Joh 10:16; Heb 13:20; 1Pe 2:25; 1Pe 5:2; 1Pe 5:4; Rev 7:17.</p> <p>S.I.T.</p> <p>SOUL The Hebrew word nephesh, &ldquo;soul,&rdquo; is also used for the life of the body of people and animals. Gen. 9:4; 35:18; Exod. 21:23; Lev. 17:11, 14; 24:17, 18; Num. 35:31; Deut. 12:23; 19:21; 2 Sam. 1:9; Job 12:10; Prov. 12:10; Jer. 38:16; Jonah 1:14.</p> <p>SOUL Gen. 37:21; Acts 2:41;<br /> &nbsp;</p> <p>SPURIOUS TEXTS</p> <p>Here are all the scriptures in the REV that are wrapped in double square</p> <p>brackets and grayed out or have grayed out sections:</p> <p>Prov 3:3</p> <p>Matt 12:47; 17:21; 18:11; 23:14</p> <p>Mark 7:16; 9:44, 46; 11:26; 15:28; 16:9-20</p> <p>Luke 17:36; 22:43-44; 23:17</p> <p>John 5:3-4; 7:53-8:11</p> <p>Acts 8:37; 15:34; 24:6-8; 28:29</p> <p>Rom 16:24</p> <p>2 Pet 3:18</p> <p>I think these are the only two that we think were not in the text but</p> <p>for which there is no direct textual evidence. They are not grayed out,</p> <p>but only wrapped in single square brackets:</p> <p>John 6:4 [the Passover]</p> <p>1 Cor 14:34-35</p> <p>SUFFERING Col. 1:24 1 Kings 14:13</p> <p>TEMPLE Praying toward the Temple, see 1 Kings 8:30</p> <p>TEN COMMANDMENTS Exodus 19:3</p> <p>TEXTS NOT ORIGINAL Prov 3:3; Matt 12:47; 17:21; 18:11; 23:14; Mark 7:16; 9:44, 46; 11:26; 15:28; 16:9-20; Luke 17:36; 22:43-44; 23:17; John 5:3-4; 7:53-8:11; Acts 8:37; 15:34; 24:6-8; 28:29; Rom 16:24; 2 Pet 3:18. I (Rob) think these are the only two that we think were not in the text but for which there is no direct textual evidence. They are not grayed out, but only wrapped in single square brackets: John 6:4 [the Passover]; 1 Cor 14:34-35</p> <p>TITHE 2 Cor. 9:7</p> <p>TRIBES OF ISRAEL REGATHERED: Isa. 11:11-12; 27:13; 56:8; 66:20; Jer. 12:15; 15:15-17; 23:3-8; 29:14; 31:8; 32:37-38, 42-44; 33:10-13; Ezek. 11:17, 28:25; 34:11-13; 36:24; 37:21; 39:28; Hos. 1:11; Amos 9:14-15; Micah 2:12; Zeph. 3:18-20; Zech. 8:7-8; 10:6.</p> <p>TRINITY 2 Thess. 1:12 &ndash; Gordon Fee [NICNT], a Trinitarian, writes, &ldquo;This [that both God and Jesus are in the verse] would hardly need further comment, except for the note in the TNIV: &lsquo;Or [the grace of] of God and Lord, Jesus Christ.&rsquo; Although this note renders what is a grammatical possibility, two matters stand strongly against it as a probability. First, despite how some would read this passage, as well as Romans 9:5 and Titus 2:13, there is simply no incontrovertible evidence (a) that Paul ever used theos to refer to Christ&mdash;rather, it is the word he used exclusively to refer to the Father&mdash;and (b) that Paul ever used kyrios to refer to the Father, since this divine name is reserved exclusively for Christ. The definitive moment for these distinctions in Paul occurs in his next letter, in 1 Corinthians 8:6, where theos of the Shema is applied to God the Father and the kyrios to Christ the Son. Second, this doubling of God and Christ is so thoroughgoing in these two letters that one would need especially strong evidence to think otherwise here, and such evidence is precisely what is lacking. So while my theological sensitivities would love to have it so, my exegetical sensitivities will not allow it&mdash;even as an alternative in this case.&rdquo; &ldquo;Theos&rdquo; means &ldquo;God and &ldquo;kyrios&rdquo; means &ldquo;Lord&rdquo;).</p> <p>TRUST Heb. 2:13, the five C&rsquo;s of &ldquo;trust.&rdquo;</p> <p>WOMEN The Bible tells us of the important place of women in the early church. Women were the first to reach the empty tomb and to proclaim the Resurrection (Matt. 28:1&ndash;10; Mark 16:1&ndash;8; Luke 23:55&ndash;24:10; John 20:1&ndash;2, 11&ndash;18). They contended for the gospel alongside Paul (Phil. 4:2&ndash;3), taught new converts (Acts 18:24&ndash;28), prophesied (Acts 21:9), had churches in their homes (Acts 16:14&ndash;15, 40; 1 Cor. 16:19), served the church (Rom. 16:1), delivered Paul&rsquo;s epistles (v. 2), and were considered &ldquo;outstanding among the apostles&rdquo; (v. 7). [From CT Magazine Oct. 2022]</p> <p>WORSHIP 1 Chron. 29:20; 1 Kings 11:33; Matt. 4:10; 2 Chron. 7:14; 2 Kings 2:15; Gen. 49:8</p>'),
