(218, 'Ritagmc', 'Hmsreo@gmail.com', 'shelby11', 'mYMBDwwxZeApjJHeU33eNnDc0fUXJz', null, '2022-03-14 12:03:17', 0, null, null, '2023-02-01 07:56:16', '172.58.128.99', null, '4:1:56:1:-1:0~0:1:56:1:-1:0~10:1:56:0:0:0~0:1:56:1:-1:0~34:-1454:0:0:0~34:-1455:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:-1455:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:2000:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:2000:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:-3:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:-4:0:0:0~34:-3961:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:-3961:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:-4:0:0:0~34:-3950:0:0:0~34:-3:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0~34:-3:0:0:0~34:-3962:0:0:0', null, null, '<p>Paul&rsquo;s First Epistle to Timothy was likely written sometime between A.D. 64 and 65, possibly while Paul was in Macedonia (see Guide to the Scriptures, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles,&rdquo; scriptures.lds.org; 1 Timothy 1:3). Before writing this epistle, Paul had been released from his two-year imprisonment (house arrest) in Rome and was likely traveling widely, visiting regions where he had previously established branches of the Church (see Bible Dictionary, &ldquo;Pauline Epistles&rdquo;).</p> <p>Paul wrote this epistle to Timothy, who had served with Paul during his second missionary journey (see Acts 16:1&ndash;3). Following their mission, Timothy continued to be a faithful missionary and Church leader (see Acts 19:22; Philippians 2:19) and one of Paul&rsquo;s most trusted associates (see 1 Corinthians 4:17). Paul referred to Timothy as his &ldquo;own son in the faith&rdquo; (1 Timothy 1:2). Timothy&rsquo;s father was a Greek Gentile, but he had a righteous Jewish mother and grandmother who had taught him and helped him learn the scriptures (see Acts 16:1; 2 Timothy 1:5; 3:15).</p> <p>At the time this epistle was written, Timothy was serving as a Church leader in Ephesus (see 1 Timothy 1:3). Paul hinted that some members doubted Timothy&rsquo;s leadership abilities because he was young (see 1 Timothy 4:12).</p> <p>At the time this epistle was written, Timothy was serving as a Church leader in Ephesus (see 1 Timothy 1:3). Paul hinted that some members doubted Timothy&rsquo;s leadership abilities because he was young (see 1 Timothy 4:12).</p> <p>Paul suggested guidelines to help Timothy identify worthy candidates to serve as bishops or deacons (see 1 Timothy 3). His guidelines helped highlight the responsibility of Church leaders to provide for members&rsquo; temporal and spiritual needs (see 1 Timothy 5). Paul also addressed the common false idea of asceticism&mdash;the belief that greater spirituality could be attained through strict self-denial. For example, he warned that some Church members would apostatize and promote the belief that marriage should be forbidden (see 1 Timothy 4:1&ndash;3). To counteract this and other harmful and apostate influences, Paul gave instructions to Timothy to teach sound doctrine (see 1 Timothy 1:3&ndash;4, 10; 4:1&ndash;6, 13, 16).</p>'),
